                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-158327 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-alzheimers-disease tag-ice-cream-and-frozen-desserts des-alzheimers-disease des-ice-cream-and-frozen-desserts news_keywords-alzheimers news_keywords-ice-cream"
                                id="post-158327">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Dad&#x2019;s Last Ice Cream</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By SARA FAITH ALTERMAN			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-10-22T07:45:46+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 22, 2015 3:45 am</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 22, 2015 3:45 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My father grew up in Perkasie, Pa., a Bucks County blip that has been twice decimated by fire; once in the 1890s, and once again in the 1980s. There&#x2019;s a Dairy Queen near the center of town, by a ball field, and
                                        a historic carousel that whinnies to life only a few times a year. When you asked Dad to reminisce about his childhood, the first thing he&#x2019;d mention and the only thing he&#x2019;d talk about in real detail
                                        was that Dairy Queen. He especially loved some frozen drink called the Mr. Misty, which may have set the tone for a lifetime of adding honorifics to inanimate objects. When I was 15 I was humiliated &#x2014; God,
                                        Dad! &#x2014; when he popped his head into a sleepover, tossed me my favorite pillow, and announced that I&#x2019;d forgotten Mr. Squishy.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My childhood treats came packaged as strange little adventures. We lived in a suburb of Boston, one of those especially New England-y parts of New England, where every clam shack and hamburger stand was a clapboard
                                        mom-and-pop affair. Once in a while on a warm summer evening, my parents would fold down the back seat of our tomato-colored station wagon and line it with sleeping bags. My brother, Daniel, and I would throw on
                                        our breeziest PJs and hop in, protected from the blast of air-conditioning by slippery cocoons of down. We&#x2019;d drive to Erikson&#x2019;s Ice Cream, and Dad would bring everyone a cup of their favorite: bubble
                                        gum for Dan, cookies and cream for me, maple walnut for Mom and a combo of coffee ice cream and orange sherbet for himself. &#x201C;The flavor!&#x201D; he&#x2019;d croon every couple of spoonfuls. &#x201C;It&#x2019;s
                                        extraordinary!&#x201D;</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When I got pregnant in May 2014, I cried. Not happy tears, but miserable, self-pitying blubbering. A woman could lose herself to a baby, I knew. Some women never find themselves again.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-158327"></span></p>
                                    <div class="w480">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/22/opinion/22PRIVATE/22PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/22/opinion/22PRIVATE/22PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/10/22/opinion/22PRIVATE/22PRIVATE-blog480.jpg" id="100000003991406"
                                                    width="480" height="662" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="662">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="480">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Rebecca Clarke</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My father was so excited to become a grandfather. But Dad, I&#x2019;d said. You already are a grandfather. And he was. Not in a &#x201C;life begins at conception&#x201D; kind of way, but because my brother had two daughters.
                                        Not secret daughters, just daughters. Grandchildren.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The following week, or maybe it was two weeks, my 69-year-old Dad learned that he had Alzheimer&#x2019;s disease, and it moved fast. By August he couldn&#x2019;t use the coffee maker, by September he couldn&#x2019;t
                                        watch movies without becoming hopelessly lost. And all the while, my belly grew. In the early fall I took him and his brother Jay to Perkasie for what I called the Hometown Nostalgia Send-Off Tour, and on the drive
                                        out there the only way Dad could make sense of where we were was in relation to the Pennsylvania Turnpike and, once in Perkasie, that good ol&#x2019; Dairy Queen.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We took pictures in front of their childhood home, the house where my grandfather installed a fountain in the living room at my grandmother&#x2019;s request, where my grandfather laid a brick retaining wall and built
                                        a crude but still-standing wooden fence, the house where my grandfather was found on the kitchen floor after a fatal heart attack. I think it was Jay who found him. We&#x2019;ve never really talked about it.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Right after my son, Colin, was born in January, my parents came to visit us in San Francisco. Our tiny rental house was an early-20th-century craftsman, identical to the house next door; the builder had erected one
                                        for himself and one for his daughter. In 1945 &#x2014; the year my father was born &#x2014; my house had been a minor character in a sad scandal. A man named August DeMont lived there, and one morning he took his
                                        5-year-old daughter, Marilyn, to the Golden Gate Bridge and convinced her to jump. Then, he followed.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In the middle of the night, when my baby son was inconsolable and my postpartum hormones raged like a pack of furious bears, I&#x2019;d think about August DeMont and how he&#x2019;d probably sat in the very room where
                                        I myself felt one sad poem away from sticking my head in the oven. I&#x2019;d think about my own father, and how he&#x2019;d driven extra carefully on those Erikson&#x2019;s excursions, because his kids were in
                                        the way back without seatbelts. And I&#x2019;d look at my own child and think, no matter how bad this gets, no matter how much you scream or how little I sleep, and even though I wasn&#x2019;t really sure if I wanted
                                        you, I will never hurt you.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">During that San Francisco visit it became clunk-on-the-head clear that Dad was becoming more of a baby every day, while the baby became more of a grown-up. They&#x2019;d both get food on their faces and need help cleaning
                                        it off, they both produced a lot of indeterminate mouth noises and unapologetic other-body-parts noises. One progressed while the other regressed.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By the summer, Dad had disappeared into his own brain. He had moments of clarity, sure, but for the most part he lived in a world where his nursing home was under attack, where men with knives sawed at his curtains.
                                        He alternately saw my mother as his greatest love and the hateful woman who&#x2019;d ruined his life by choosing to hospitalize and, later, institutionalize him after he&#x2019;d had a series of medical incidents
                                        that would have been relatively benign for a person without Alzheimer&#x2019;s. A kidney stone here, a quick laparoscopic gallbladder removal there. But Dad would forget where he was and rip out his IVs and catheters
                                        in an absolute panic, because he didn&#x2019;t understand why his body was crawling with tubes.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I took Colin to see my father a few times right before he died in July, by which point he&#x2019;d lost most of his ability to speak or move. All of that tube yanking had opened the door to infection, and one had barged
                                        right in. Appearance-wise, Dad was full doomsday bunker crackpot. Crazy hair, wild eyes. Nobody could get near him to trim his beard or brush his teeth. If he were a stranger on the sidewalk, I&#x2019;d have crossed
                                        the street.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He wouldn&#x2019;t eat &#x2014; couldn&#x2019;t, really, and my mom had taken to bringing him ice cream every day, because it was the only thing he&#x2019;d allow in or even near his mouth. She&#x2019;d spoon-feed him
                                        coffee ice cream and orange sherbet, using a small sponge to mop up when he forgot to swallow. I took a turn once, feeding him as gently as I could. Are you ready for another bite, Dad? I&#x2019;d ask, and he&#x2019;d
                                        sort of gurgle a small noise of affirmation so I&#x2019;d feed him some more. And then &#x2014; &#x201C;The flavor!&#x201D; he managed, and I nearly had a heart attack. &#x201C;It&#x2019;s extraordinary! Extraordinary.&#x201D;
                                        And then he closed his eyes. Not to die, not yet. Just to be satisfied with the taste of his favorite ice cream.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After Dad had eaten as much as he could handle, I held Colin close to my heart and close to my father&#x2019;s face, so he might see his grandson. Dad reached a very shaky hand toward the baby, and when I saw his cracked
                                        and yellow fingernails my first instinct was to move away. Dad must have understood somehow, because he went for Colin&#x2019;s leg instead, and gingerly stroked my son&#x2019;s plump thigh, encased like a sausage
                                        in a pair of stretchy baby pants. &#x201C;Let him live,&#x201D; Dad croaked, and I wondered if this was poignant counsel or if Dad were hallucinating that we were in a war zone.</p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That ice cream turned out to be my father&#x2019;s last meal. Later, back at my mother&#x2019;s house, the rest of the family gathered around while I fed Colin his first bite of solid food: a jar of neon goo that purported
                                        to be &#x201C;macaroni and cheese.&#x201D; He absolutely hated it, and as his face puckered and a disgusted wail gathered in the back of his throat, we all laughed, then cried, and I resolved to stop worrying about
                                        losing myself to a baby and instead to give myself to him. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Sara Faith Alterman is a writer and a co-producer of the stage show &#x201C;<a href="//getmortified.com/">Mortified</a>.&#x201D;</em></p>
                                    <footer class="story-footer">
                                        <div class="story-meta">
                                            <p class="story-print-citation">A version of this article appears in print on 10/25/2015, on page <span itemprop="printSection">SR</span><span itemprop="printPage">7</span> of the <span itemprop="printEdition">NewYork</span> edition with the
                                                headline: Dadu2019s Last Ice Cream.</p>
                                        </div>
                                    </footer>
                                </div>
